----
# Other option
`JsonConvert.DefaultSettings = () =&gt; new JsonSerializerSettings (...)`

[JsonConvert.DefaultSettings Property](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/P_Newtonsoft_Json_JsonConvert_DefaultSettings.htm)

&gt;Gets or sets a function that creates default JsonSerializerSettings. Default settings are automatically used by serialization methods on JsonConvert, and ToObject&lt;T&gt; () and FromObject(Object) on JToken. To serialize without using any default settings create a JsonSerializer with Create().

The call to `AddMvc` returns an [`IMvcBuilder`](https://github.com/aspnet/AspNetCore/blob/release/3.0/src/Mvc/Mvc.Core/src/DependencyInjection/IMvcBuilder.cs) implementation, which has a corresponding [`AddJsonOptions`](https://github.com/aspnet/AspNetCore/blob/release/3.0/src/Mvc/Mvc.Core/src/DependencyInjection/MvcCoreMvcBuilderExtensions.cs#L51) extension method. As confirmed in the comments, you&#39;re using the new-style `AddControllers` call, which also returns an `IMvcBuilder` implementation. You can chain this in the same way you would chain with `AddMvc`:

    services.AddControllers()
        .AddJsonOptions(options =&gt;
        {
            // ...
        });

Note that `options` here is no longer for JSON.NET options, but for the new `System.Text.Json` approach. If you need some of the flexibility of JSON.NET, you can revert to using this, as described in [tymtam&#39;s answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58392090/2630078)

